<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="47" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,354,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known from the Mausam, Sur Luite (both tributaries of the Tuivai River), Tlawng and Tuirial rivers in Mizoram, northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[515,573,188,212]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">India</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[589,657,188,212]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,912,935]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,198,881]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,891]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Map showing collecting localities of Glyptothorax maceriatus. Each point represents two localities." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/214999/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number box="[642,657,188,212]" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). The Tlawng, Tuirial and Tuivai rivers form part of the Barak River drainage, which is itself part of the Surma-Meghna River system.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
